↳ In-reply-to » @xuu You can’t tell it from the screenshot and that’s my point. 😅 I was scaring at the screen, just like you, trying to figure out what’s going on. Then I read the spoiler on StackOverflow and, yeah, the code box actually has a scroll bar, but it’s not visible …

@movq@www.uninformativ.de I agree with you, matrices are probably the only place where this makes sense, even then its more of a “syntactic” sugar really, because the computer sure as hell doesn’t just “multiply” the two matrices together 😅 – So like generics, I really don’t think we need “operating overloading” in Go 😢

↳ In-reply-to » @xuu You can’t tell it from the screenshot and that’s my point. 😅 I was scaring at the screen, just like you, trying to figure out what’s going on. Then I read the spoiler on StackOverflow and, yeah, the code box actually has a scroll bar, but it’s not visible …

@movq@www.uninformativ.de Also as an aside, I really don’t know what problem we’re trying to solve by adding “operator overloading” in Go. It feels like Java/Python influencing the language because they can’t do fancy shit like, oh I dunno, something I used to do in Python:

some_object + some_other_obj

🤦‍♂️
